Column Comment.0: VELOCITY VOLUME IDENTIFIER: unique identifier for this velocity volume.
Column Comment.1: VOLUME POINT: unique identifier for the point in the velocity volume.
Column Comment.2: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether this row of data is currently eitheractive / valid (Y) or inactive / invalid (N).
Column Comment.3: BIN GRID ID: Primary unique identifier for Bin grid.
Column Comment.4: BIN POINT ID: Unique identifier for the Bin Point.
Column Comment.5: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.6: REFERENCE VELOCITY COMPUTATION METHOD: A reference table identifyingmethods for computing seismic velocity. For example, checkshot survey,interpolation...
Column Comment.7: EFFECTIVE DATE: The date that the data in this row first came into effect.
Column Comment.8: EXPIRY DATE: The date that the data in this row was no longer active or in effect.
Column Comment.9: LATITUDE: The latitude of the point in the volume, especially in the case where thepoint is neither in SEIS POINT nor in SEIS BIN POINT.
Column Comment.10: LONGITUDE: Thelongitude of the point in the volume, especially in the case wherethe point is neither in SEIS POINT nor in SEIS BIN POINT.
Column Comment.11: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should be created.
Column Comment.12: GEOPHONE MEASURED DEPTH: Measured depth from the surface to the locationof the geophone.
Column Comment.14: RECEIVER VERTICAL DEPTH: Vertical depth of the record.
Column Comment.16: REMARK: Narrative remarks relating to this row of data.
Column Comment.17: SEISMIC POINT ID: Unique identifier for each seismic point
Column Comment.18: SEISMIC SET: A seismic set is a super type of various types of seismic collections.
Column Comment.19: SEISMIC SET SUBTYPE: The seismic set type column is used to enforce arelationship between the SEIS SET supertype and its valid sub types. Values for thiscolumn must be the name of the table that is the valid sub type for this row of data.Valid entries include SEIS_LINE, SEIS_SEGMENT, SEIS_SURVEY, SEIS_PLAN,SEIS_WELL, SEIS_PROC_SET, SEIS_INTERP_SET or SEIS_3D.
Column Comment.20: OBSERVED TIME: Wellbore seismic survey time.
Column Comment.22: SEISMIC SET: A seismic set is a super type of various types of seismic collections.
Column Comment.23: SEISMIC SET SUBTYPE: The seismic set type column is used to enforce arelationship between the SEIS SET supertype and its valid sub types. Values for thiscolumn must be the name of the table that is the valid sub type for this row of data.Valid entries include SEIS_LINE, SEIS_SEGMENT, SEIS_SURVEY, SEIS_PLAN,SEIS_WELL, SEIS_PROC_SET, SEIS_INTERP_SET or SEIS_3D.
Column Comment.24: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.25: SOURCE MEASURED DEPTH: Measured depth from the surface to the location ofthe source
Column Comment.27: SOURCE VERTICAL DEPTH: Vertical depth of the source.
Column Comment.29: VELOCITY: The value of the velocity determined.
Column Comment.30: VELOCITY AZIMUTH: The azmuth of the velocity measurement.
Column Comment.31: DEPTH: the depth for the velocity pick.
Column Comment.32: VELOCITY INCLINATION: The inclination of the velocity measurement
Column Comment.35: VELOCITY TYPE: A reference table identifying the valid types of seismic velocity.Horizontal velocities and vertical velocites are typical types.
Column Comment.36: VELOCITY X: The X component of the velocity measurement.
Column Comment.37: VELOCITY Y: The Y component of the velocity measurement.
Column Comment.38: VELOCITY Z: The Z component of the velocity measurement.
Column Comment.39: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.40: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.41: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.42: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.43: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.44: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.45: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
